                        General Marshall</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1946v09</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d668</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">668</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1946-07-13T00:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1946-07-13T23:59:59-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-07-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-07-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="668" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d668">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Marshall Mission Files, Lot 54–D270:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Walter S. Robertson</persName> to
                        General <persName type="to">Marshall</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-07-13">13 July
                            1946</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5378. For your information the pertinent parts of Generalissimo’s order of 1 July
                    as cited in your 1077<note n="15" xml:id="d668fn15">July 8, <ref target="#pg_1326">p. 1326</ref>.</note> and 1087<note n="16" xml:id="d668fn16">July 9, <ref target="#pg_1335">p. 1335</ref>.</note> have
                    been transmitted <pb facs="1365" n="1353" xml:id="pg_1353"/> to all field team
                    chairmen, as well as the information contained in your 1084.<note n="17" xml:id="d668fn17">July 9, <ref target="#pg_1331">p. 1331</ref>.</note>
                    Senior field team chairmen have been instructed to determine when orders of
                    Generalissimo and General Chou En-lai are in the hands of subordinate commanders
                    within reach of our field teams. In no case were the contents nor the gist of
                    the contents of Mao Tse-tung’s orders learned by US members of field teams. US
                    Branch Executive Headquarters likewise without information on contents of
                    order.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
